ce:section.ce:para:
Multiple phenology models have been widely used in predictions and evaluations of spring phenology. In this study, we employed five representative spring phenology models. According to the number of preceding development phases, these models can be classified into one-phase, two-phase, and multi-phase models (Piao et al., 2019). The models included:

                              (1)


                                 Thermal Time model with one-phase, with leaf growth initiated when the accumulated heat exceeds a critical threshold (calculated by Eqs. (1)–(3) in Table 1
                                 ) (Cannell and Smith, 1983);


                              (2)


                                 Sequential model with two-phase, with explicit consideration of the developmental phases preceding leaf unfolding (calculated by Eqs. (4)–(9) in Table 1) (Hänninen, 1990). In the first stage, the vegetation needed to accumulate a certain amount of chilling to “wake up” from endodormancy. The second stage was similar to the Thermal Time model—the leaf began growth when the critical heat index was met;


                              (3)


                                 Parallel model with two-phase, which resembled the Sequential model (calculated by Eqs. (10)–(13) in Table 1) (Landsberg, 1974; Kramer, 1994), but the Parallel model accumulated chilling- and heat-indices simultaneously. The accumulated rate of heat was controlled by the accumulated rate of chilling;


                              (4)


                                 Unichill model with two-phase, which had the same processes as the Sequential model, but this model had a new method for calculating the accumulated rate of chilling (calculated by Eqs. (14)–(17) in Table 1) (Chuine, 2000);


                              (5)


                                 DORMPHOT model with multi-phase, which integrated the effect of photoperiod (calculated by Eqs. (18)–(25) in Table 1) (Caffarra et al., 2011). The first stage was triggered by both photoperiod and temperature, and the vegetation was induced to enter the state of endodormancy when the critical threshold was reached. The second stage was the accumulation of chilling and then awakened the vegetation from the endodormancy. The third stage was also to accumulate a certain amount of heat and the accumulated rate was determined by both the photoperiod and the accumulated chilling.
